":"1398–1478","1490":"1490","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","about 1415":"okolo 1415","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1497":"1497","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","about 1442":"okolo 1442","about 1440":"okolo 1440","Membury, Devon, England,":"Membury, Devon, Anglie","Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Membury, Devon, Anglie, United Kingdom","Membury, Devon, England":"Membury, Devon, Anglie","Wembury Parish, Devon, England":"Wembury, Devon, Anglie","Devon, England":"Devon, Anglie"},"da":{"about 1415–1497":"omkring 1415–1497","1415–1497":"1415–1497","1420–1487":"1420–1487","1442–1490":"1442–1490","1380–1467":"1380–1467","1398–1478":"1398–1478","1490":"1490","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","about 1415":"omkring 1415","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1497":"1497","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","about 1442":"omkring 1442","about 1440":"omkring 1440","Membury, Devon, England,":"Membury, Devon, England","Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Membury, Devon, England":"Membury, Devon, England","Wembury Parish, Devon, England":"Wembury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"nl":{"about 1415–1497":"circa 1415–1497","1415–1497":"1415–1497","1420–1487":"1420–1487","1442–1490":"1442–1490","1380–1467":"1380–1467","1398–1478":"1398–1478","1490":"1490","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","about 1415":"circa 1415","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1497":"1497","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","about 1442":"circa 1442","about 1440":"circa 1440","Membury, Devon, England,":"Membury, Devon, England","Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Membury, Devon, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Membury, Devon, England":"Membury, Devon, England","Wembury Parish, Devon, England":"Wembury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England"},"en":{"about 1415–1497":"about 1415–1497","1415–1497":"1415–1497","1420–1487":"1420–1487","1442–1490":"1442–1490","1380–1467":"1380–1467","1398–1478":"1398–1478","1490":"1490","1380":"1380","1415":"1415","1467":"1467","1478":"1478","about 1415":"about 1415","1455":"1455","1487":"1487","1497":"1497","1398":"1398","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","about 1442":"about 1442","about 1440":"about 1440","Membury, Devon, England,":"Membury, Devon, England","Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom":"Membury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Membury, Devon, England":"Membury, Devon, England","Wembury Parish, Devon, England":"Wembury, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Perry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Welsh: Anglicized form of Welsh <i>ap Herry</i> ‘son of <i>Herry</i>’, a variant of the personal name <i>Harry</i> (see   Harris  ).","English: topographic name for someone who lived near a pear tree (Middle English <i>piri(e)</i>, <i>peri(e)</i>, <i>puri(e)</i>, Old English <i>pirige, pyrige</i>), or a habitational name for someone who owned or came from a place so named. This surname and a number of variants have been established in Ireland since the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Peery","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Perry  , taken to Ireland at the time of thePlantation of Ulster and in the Cromwellian period."]},{"name":"Pear","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Dov.","English: topographic name from residence by a pear tree (Middle English <i>pere</i>, Old English <i>peru</i>, <i>pere</i>). Compare   Perry  .","English: nickname from Middle English <i>pere</i>, Old French <i>per</i>, <i>peer</i> ‘peer or paragon’, also ‘companion’."]},{"name":"Peary","meanings":["English (mainly northern): variant of   Perry  .","History: Robert E. Peary (1856–1920) was a U.S.-born explorer, who in 1909 led the first successful expedition to the North Pole. Peary Land in the north of Greenland is named after him, as he explored there in 1892 and 1900."]},{"name":"Perrie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Perry   2. Alternatively, perhaps from the Old French personal name <i>Pierre</i>; see   Pierce  ."]},{"name":"Harris","meanings":["English (southern England and south Wales): from the personal name   Harry   + genitival <i>-s</i>. This surname is also established in Ireland, taken there principally during the Plantation of Ulster. However, in some cases, particularly in families coming from County Mayo, <i>Harris</i> can be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hEarchadha</b>. This surname is also very common among African Americans.","American shortened and altered form of Greek surnames begining with <i>Cha(r)-</i>, such as <b>Chasandrinos</b> (variant of <b>Kassandrinos</b>, a habitational name from the Kassandra peninsula of Chalkidiki), and various patronymics from the personal name <i>Charalampos</i> (see   Charos  ). In North America, the surname <i>Harris</i> may possibly also originate from a transferred use of the Greek personal (given) name <i>Charis</i> or <i>Harris</i> (shortened forms of <i>Charalampos</i>) as a surname (i.e. as a replacement of the original surname).","Americanized form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames."]},{"name":"Perryman","meanings":["English (Devon): elaborated form of   Perry  , with Middle English <i>man</i>, probably denoting one who lived near a pear tree; see   Pearman  ."]}]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":40,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Christopher William Perry was born about 1415, in Membury, Devon, England, his father, Christopher Peyre, was 36 and his mother, Blanche De Water, was 18. He married Emma Hele about 1440, in Membury, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1497, in his hometown, at the age of 83."},"et":{"about 1415–1497":"umbes 1415–1497","1415–1497":"1415–1497","1420–1487":"1420–1487","1442–1490":"1442–1490","1380–1467":"1380–1467","1398–1478":"1398–1478","1490":"1490","1380":"